GDP and Smoking



By Rod Rahmjoo and Sepehr Tabaeizadeh


Introduction and Motivation

Being Immigrants from a third world country, we have both seen our fair share of smokers. Since both of us are from Iran, we both know how prevalent the issue is there. We both have countless family and friends in Iran who are addicted to smoking. Since we now live in the United States, a first world country, we now know that this is not the case for everyone around the world. We hypothesized that country income (GDP) may play a major role when it comes to the number of smokers in any given country. In order to examine that hypothesis, and in order find out some of the root causes of smoking, we decided to do some more research in that area.

Data Tidying

Now that we have loaded the ‘somkers_gdp.csv’ into the 'data' table, we should now clean the input. By clean the input, I mean remove all rows that do not have a value for both GDP and Smoking Prevalence, because if both of these values are missing, the country does not give any useful input for smoking.

In [ ]:
data = data.loc[(data['Year'] >= 2000) & (data['Year'] <= 2016)]
#fix the naming because the naming convention is too long
data = data.rename(columns={'Smoking prevalence, total (ages 15+)': 'Smoking Prevalence', \
                     'GDP per capita, PPP (constant 2011 international $)': 'GDP'})
            
data = data.loc[data['Smoking Prevalence'].notna() | data['GDP'].notna()]
data = data.reset_index(drop = True)

Fixing the missing data

Now that we have both datasets, we should update the 'data' list to get rid of as many missing values as possible. We can do this using the 'Entity' column in the 'data' list since no row in the 'data' list has it's 'Entity' value missing. If we cannot find a match due to spelling differences, we can use the Code column if that column does not contain a missing value.

In [ ]:
#copy continent val from continent to data

#all rows where Continent is NA
for ind, row in data[data['Continent'].isna()].iterrows():
  Entity = row['Entity']

  helper_row = continents[continents['Country'] == Entity]
  helper_row = helper_row[helper_row['Region'].notna()]

  #check if string is NaN
  if helper_row.shape[0] > 0:
    #set code
    data.loc[ind, 'Continent'] = helper_row['Region'].iloc[0]
  else:

    Code = row['Code']
    
    second_help = continents[continents['Code'] == Code]
    second_help = second_help[second_help['Code'].notna()]

    if second_help.shape[0] > 0:
      data.loc[ind, 'Continent'] = second_help['Region'].iloc[0]

Since we will be using 'Entity' and 'Code' for the same purpose (as an identifier to communicate) and 'Entity' is the only one out of the two that does not have any missing values, we can ignore 'Code' and drop it's values.

Summary of the Columns

  • Entity: The country in which the data was collected.
  • Code: Abbreviation of the country name (dropped).
  • Year: The year in which the data was collected.
  • Smoking Prevalence: Percentage of people above 15 who smoke in the given year and country.
  • GDP: Gross Domestic Product of the country in the given year.
  • Continent: The Region in which the country lays.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Now that we have dealt with all the missing data and we have removed all the columns that we do not need. It is time to do some analyis on our data. Our goal is to find out if there is any correlation or relationship between the GDP of each country and the percentage of people above 15 who smoke.

Smoking (Prevalence vs Year) and (GDP vs Year)

It is a good idea to create a graph of Smoking Prevalence vs Year. This will help us find out if there is any correlation between the year and smoking prevalence and also if there is any correlation between the year and GDP. This can help us later on with our ultimate goal which is to find out if there is any correlation between GDP and Smoking Prevalence.

To do this we are taking the mean of the Smoking prevalence among the countries in each year. This will help us to better visually analyse the data.

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))

for idx, row in data.groupby('Year'):
  
  plt.scatter(row['Year'].iloc[0],row['Smoking Prevalence'].mean())

plt.title('Prevalence vs Year', size = 15)
plt.xlabel('Year', size = 15)
plt.ylabel('Prevalence', size = 15)
#making plots more enjoyable
Out[ ]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Prevalence')

From the plot we can see that there is a decreasing trend between Smoking Prevalence and year, since as the year increases the Smoking Prevalence decreases. For next step it would be great to create a plot of mean GDP per year vs Year to see weather or not GDP follows the same downards trend as we saw above or if there is any type of visible relation between the two graphs.

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))

for idx, row in data.groupby('Year'):
  
  plt.scatter(row['Year'].iloc[0],row['GDP'].mean())
  
plt.title('GDP vs Year',size=15)
plt.xlabel('Year', size= 15)
plt.ylabel('GDP', size = 15)
Out[ ]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'GDP')

From this graph we can see that there is a positive trend between GDP and year (unlike the negative trend in Smoking Prevelance vs Year). On average as year increases the GDP increases as well. This makes sense intuitively, because as time increases, there are different factors that would lead to this. One of these factors is inflation. Since inflation exists, even if countries produce the same amount, they do not necissarily produce the same monitary value. As time progresses, goods and services get more expensive due to inflation. Another reason for increase in GDP as time progresses is population (which increases over time on average).

Although both GDP and Smoking Prevalence are correlated with Year it does not mean that they are correlated to eachother. But that does not mean that all of the work we did above is necissarily in vain. These two graphs have given us an overview that may help us later on.

Smoking Prevalence vs Year

to better understand what kind of relationship lies between Smoking Prevalance and Year, we can plot the Smoking Prevalance vs Year graph and find the regression line.

In [ ]:
plot_data = data
plot_data = plot_data.loc[pd.notna(plot_data['Year']) & pd.notna(plot_data['Smoking Prevalence'])]
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
plt.scatter(x = plot_data['Year'], y = plot_data['Smoking Prevalence'])
plt.title("Smoking Prevalence vs Year Regression Line", size = 15)
plt.xlabel('Year', size = 15)
plt.ylabel('Smoking Prevalence', size = 15)
x_plt = []
y_plt = []
for ind, row in plot_data.groupby('Year'):
  
  x_plt.append(row['Year'].iloc[0])
  y_plt.append(row['Smoking Prevalence'].mean())

m, b = np.polyfit(np.array(x_plt), np.array(y_plt), 1)
plt.plot(np.array(x_plt), m*np.array(x_plt)+b, color = 'red')
plt.show()

Now that we have the regression line, we can see that smoking in general decreases as the years increase. To make sure this regresion line is a good fit, we can take a look at the graph of the residuals.

In [ ]:
temp = data
temp = temp[temp['Smoking Prevalence'].notna()]

X = np.array(temp['Year']).reshape(-1,1)
y = np.array(temp['Smoking Prevalence'])

lm = LinearRegression().fit(X, y)

residuals = []
residual_years = []

#go through each of the years
for ind, row in temp.groupby('Year'):
    
    #save the current year's value into the same position as where it's residuals will be in residuals list
    curr_year = row['Year'].iloc[0]
    residual_years.append(curr_year)

    #to save the list of residuals that we will then append to the residuals list
    curr_residuals = []
    #one prediction per year so we do not need this inside the other loop
    prediction = lm.predict(curr_year.reshape(-1,1))[0]
    
    for ind2, row2 in row.iterrows():
        #concat the residuals
        curr_residuals.append(row2['Smoking Prevalence'] - prediction)
        
    #add this residual list to the list of residuals
    residuals.append(curr_residuals)


fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,10))
ax.violinplot(residuals,residual_years,showmeans=True)
ax.set_ylabel('Smoking Prevalence Residuals', fontsize=15)
ax.set_xlabel('Year', fontsize=15)
ax.set_title('Smoking Prevalence Residuals vs Year Violin Plot', fontsize=15)
#I have plotted the y = 0 line for convience
ax.axhline(y=0, color = 'black')

From the plot below we can see that there is a decreasing trend between GDP and Smoking prevalence. Since as the GDP increases then the Smoking Prevalence decreeases. We should keep this in mind in the next steps.

Smoking Prevalance vs GDP Range

Since the graph shown above is difficult to digest, lets fix that. We divide it into 4 subplots where each plot contains a subset of the years (ex: 2000-2004). Within these subplots, we can also draw the regression line associated with that subplot to see if the year makes a major difference in the predictions.

In [ ]:
plot_data = data
plot_data = plot_data.loc[pd.notna(plot_data['GDP']) & pd.notna(plot_data['Smoking Prevalence'])]
plot_data['periods'] = pd.cut(plot_data['Year'],4)
grouped_data = plot_data.groupby(['periods'])

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,4,figsize=(25,5))

for (index, (idx, gp)) in enumerate(grouped_data):

    #x_pos and y_pos used for regression line
    x_pos = []
    y_pos = []

    cmap = plt.get_cmap('gist_rainbow')
    colors = [cmap(i) for i in range(0, 5000, 1)]
    ind = 0

    # Iterate through countries
    for idx2, gp2 in gp.groupby(['Entity']):
      # Append x_pos and y_pos by each countries GDP and Smoking Prevalence respectively.
      x = gp2['GDP'].mean()
      y = gp2['Smoking Prevalence'].mean()

      color = colors[ind]
      ind += 1


      x_pos.append(x)
      y_pos.append(y)
      # Add the points to the plot
      ax[index].scatter(x=x, y=y, label = gp2.iloc[0,0], color = color)

    ax[index].grid()
    # Set y label, x label and table title
    ax[index].set_ylabel('Mean Smoking prevalence', fontsize=12)
    ax[index].set_xlabel('Mean GDP', fontsize=12)
    ax[index].set_title(f'Year Interval: {idx}', fontsize=14)
    
    # Plot the regression line
    m, b = np.polyfit(np.array(x_pos), np.array(y_pos), 1)
    ax[index].plot(np.array(x_pos), m*np.array(x_pos)+b)
    #ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1.03), prop={'size': 12}, ncol = 3) 
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(.9, -0.4),prop={'size': 12}, ncol = 4)
plt.show()

We can see that the data is not fully centered at 0 for all of the graphs for each of their respective GDP ranges. This means that we should take GDP into account when making our predictions as well. If we want to take both of these elements into account while making a prediction, we will need a multivariable linear regression instead. We can make sure that this is the case by combining all of these graphs into one.

Smoking Prevalence vs. Year (grouped by GDP Range)

Now that we know there is some kind of correlation we should find out if there is an interactoin between GDP and Year. In other words we need to see if the coef of Smoking Prevalence vs Year differs in each GDP Group.

In [ ]:
# Cut the gdp columns into 5 different groups
# For each row add the corresponding interval to the gdp groups column

#####DO NOT CHANGE temp#####
temp = temp[temp['GDP'].notna()]
temp['gdp_groups'] = pd.cut(data['GDP'],5)

data_g = temp
data_g['gdp_groups'] = pd.cut(data['GDP'],5)

# Get name of all GDP Groups in our data
data_gdp_groups = data_g.gdp_groups.unique()
# Get all years in our data
data_years = data_g['Year'].unique()
# Colors to be used for each GDP plot
gdp_colors = ['blue','black','khaki','red','green']
i = 0

# Iterate through the gdp groups
for cont in data_gdp_groups:   
    # Get all data related to the group cont
    cont_data = data_g.loc[data_g['gdp_groups'] == cont]
    # Set year column as independent variable
    x = cont_data['Year'].values.reshape(-1,1) 
    # Set Smoking Prevalence as dependent variable
    y = cont_data['Smoking Prevalence'].values.reshape(-1,1)
    
    # Create a Linear regression model and train (fit a regression line)
    reg = LinearRegression().fit(x, y)
    # Add coef and variance and intercept to a variable
    coef = reg.coef_
    var =  reg.score(x, y)
    intercept = reg.intercept_
    
    # Plot each continent life expectency and year
    plt.scatter(x, y,  color = gdp_colors[i])
    plt.plot(x, reg.predict(x), color = 'orange', linewidth=5)
    plt.title("{} GDP Group".format(cont))
    plt.ylabel("Smoking Prevalence")
    plt.xlabel("Year")
    i += 1
    plt.show()
    print('Coef:', coef[0][0])

Interpreting the Result¶

From the result above we see that the Smoking Prevalence changes each year in each different GDP_Group differently and this in fact shows us that for sure not only is there a correlation between Smoking Prevalence and Year but also there is a correlation between Smoking Prevalence and GDP. From the list above we see that for countries within the GDP group of (432.824, 26319.273] the Smoking Prevalence decreases by -0.39972577639731 per year while for countries withing groups (26319.273, 52076.934], (77834.595, 103592.256], (77834.595, 103592.256], (52076.934, 77834.595], and (103592.256, 129349.916] it changes by -0.4542129971459177, -0.4029436695692456, -0.5325160891039846, and 0.2798742138364516 respectively per year.

As we can see in most of the GDP group as the GDP and year increases the Smoking Prevalence decreases except for the last group of countries which their GDP is between (103592.256, 129349.916]. This can have several reasons, for example one can be that there are less countries in that group therefore there is less data. Also it might be because countries with a very high GDP do not follow the same trend. This could be as a result of higher advertizing of tabbaco products (such as the JUUL in the United States).

i_residuals = []
i_residual_years = []

#for all of the year groupings
for ind, row in features.groupby('Year'):
    
    #to store the order of the years
    curr_year = row['Year'].iloc[0]
    i_residual_years.append(curr_year)    
    
    #to add to residuals list later
    curr_residuals = []
    
    for ind2, row2 in row.iterrows():
        #make a prediction with all of the neccisiary parameters
        new_X = np.array(row2.drop('Smoking Prevalence'))
        prediction = lm.predict(new_X.reshape(1,-1))[0]        
        #keep track of the residual
        curr_residuals.append(row2['Smoking Prevalence'] - prediction)
    
    #concat to the residuals lists
    i_residuals.append(curr_residuals)


#plot

Conclusion

Our analysis shows that Smoking Prevalence decreases as year increases. This result make sense because there are more researches now available about impact of smoking on human body and people became more aware about dangerousness of smoking. Also there are more restrictions on when and who can smoke now a days compared to before. Therefore, it makes a lot of sense that Smoking Prevalence decreases as the year increases.

On the other hand we noticed that it is not only year that affects Smoking Prevalence, but there is also an interaction between year and the country GDP. From our analysis we notice that there exist a decreasing trend between Smoking Prevalence and GDP which means that when the GDP increases then the Smoking Prevalence decreases.To achieve this we divided the data into 5 main groups based on their GDP and compared the GDP affect on Smoking prevalence in each of those groups separately. Since we noticed that there is an interaction between GDP and Year, we knew that we should use an interaction term.

After fitting a linear regression model for smoking prevalence including a term for an interaction between GDP and Year, we get the coefficient for each of the GDP groups. In other words we see by how many percentage smoking prevalence in in each GDP group changes. The result is as follow:

  • (432.824, 26319.273] : -0.39972577639731
  • (26319.273, 52076.934] : -0.4542129971459177
  • (77834.595, 103592.256] : -0.4029436695692456
  • (52076.934, 77834.595] : -0.5325160891039846
  • (103592.256, 129349.916] : 0.2798742138364516

As we can see in the results above the Smoking Prevalence has decreasing trend in all of the groups except for the last group which has a positive trend. This can be for several reasons but the main reason we can think of is that since there are not that many countries have a GDP in within that interval there is not enough data in that interval to get accurate result. Also it can be because of advertisements that are being done in those countries. If we look even closer we see that in most cases the coefficient increases as we go to intervals with higher GDP range which agree with what discovered earlier.
